    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm worried about the corners though. because it's a small bathroom, there's a lot of tight angles and some of the seams meet right at the ceiling. how do i make sure the mud doesn't crack or pull away from the edges in those tight spots?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Corners and tight angles are where the real trouble starts, so you need to treat those spots with extra care. When dealing with those tight corners, you can use a smaller taping knife, or even a putty knife, to carefully feather the compound into the corner. It's important to build up the mud in thin layers, especially where the drywall meets the ceiling, so you don't create a thick, hard ridge that will crack later.",
      "source": "target",
